-- China shares tepid after MSCI keeps mainland stocks out of benchmark index
-- By Grace Li
-- Wed Jun 11, 2014 03:06AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 11 (Reuters) - China shares ended flat on Wednesday after equity index provider MSCI decided not to add A-shares to its benchmark emerging markets index, which dented hopes of hefty capital inflows for mainland markets.  [ID:nL2N0OR2HB]

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> edged up 0.1 percent at 2,054.95 points. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings finished barely changed. Chinese dairy companies rose after the official Economy & Nation Weekly reported that the central government had approved a restructuring plan for the industry.